              h2.display-4 About Me
              p I&apos;m just a kid trying to pay my way through college, but I want to help create real savings and retirements on my way through. Currently a high school senior, my goal by 30 is to create an online broker that combines traditional equity, bond, and cryptocurrency markets in a decentralized system that rewards independent money managers, allows everyone to easily invest, opens active trading to the world, and helps replace existing banking systems. With that said, I&apos;m a long way away from where I need to be to start that venture, hence me going to college.
              p Wooten Stock Picks sprouted not out of necessity but rather as a realization of how I could help others. Let me explain some of my background.
    section
      .container
        .row.align-items-center
          .col-lg-6.order-lg-2
            .p-5
              img.img-fluid(src='/static/wooten-stock-picks/img/biopic2.jpg' alt='John F. Wooten')/
          .col-lg-6.order-lg-1
            .p-5
              p Freshman summer, I got a minimum-wage job at a Subway. I worked hard there and was training new employees and opening the store alone by the beginning of sophomore year. I kept working long hours at Subway during the school year until April. During the year, I built my first computer and used it to research the stock market because my dad sells bonds for a living. When I quit Subway, I immediately used my freed-up time to research tons of information about the stock market. Since I saved all the money I made at Subway, I built my own diversified long-term portfolios to invest my money into. Then, once the school year ended, I started day trading every morning. I loved what I did and was always excited to manage my positions on a market day. Plus, trading in the stock market allowed me to schedule my day around the opening bell instead of an opening shift. This freed up time in the morning for me to practice for my school&apos;s Cross Country team! I consistently managed my long-term positions towards the end of the day to keep my gains above the markets.
    section
      .container
        .row.align-items-center
          .col-lg-6
            .p-5
              img.img-fluid(src='https://via.placeholder.com/1024?text=Photo+2' alt='John F. Wooten')/
          .col-lg-6
            .p-5
              p Once junior year came around, I quickly realized that I could not trade the opening bell during second period. However, I remembered that I saw a computer article about cryptocurrencies and GPU shortages, so I started looking into the emerging cryptocurrency space. I decided to use my limited background in computers and ready-to-invest cash to build an eight-card mining computer. Additionally, I started to swing trade cryptocurrencies just like stocks because they were volatile all day and all night rather than the stock market&apos;s open-to-close trading hours. Between classes, I quickly managed long-term positions and looked for new investment opportunities on the fly. If I saw any amazing conditions, I usually placed orders between classes.
              p I loved crypto-trading and kept with it passionately for the first semester of junior year. On the other hand, I had tons of issues with my mining computer. I troubleshot the machine for months and months after Cross Country practice before I finally got it stable in January. This tough computer work gave me a great understanding of technology and a tremendous appreciation for the immense amount of work that goes behind software engineering. When the second semester of junior year started, I decided to shift my focus away from trading to focus on bigger projects. I dove deep into research about what was really behind the technology I traded for the past six months, which lead to the creation of MonerAds.
    section
